history.text: Hey! How are things going today?
Going well. You?
Fine - it looks like spring is about to happen her.
Have you seen that movie?
Yes, I have seen the Great Gatsby. It surprises me that with the big names in the cast that critics didn't like it better
I know! I didn't see it but I saw the trailer and it did look good. At least spectacular.
Did you like it?
I'm not s big fan of the story line in the first place, plus the book is way better.

That I don't doubt. It's a classic after all. And Baz Luhrman tends to turn everything
 he touches into an extravaganza.
Did you like the work of Joel Edgerton in it though?
I really did. Tom is so unlikable and he did a great job making you hate his character. He deserved more screen time
I usually love it when actors make unlikable characters interesting.

I usually love Carey Mulligan but I suspe
ct she was just OK in that movie.
Personally I just hate Daisy's character. She is selfish and has no real understanding of herself, so it was personally hard to like her no matter the actress.
I see what you mean.
I think that Macguire does a good job with the introduction of the movie in the opening scene though. He really takes you back.
I like him as an actor most of the time.
From the beginning, he really makes you like Gatsby and tries to explain how good of a friend he was.
And although I don't really like Di Caprio as a person, I think he often does a good job in movies.
It's kind of a risky casting though - Tobey Macguire and Di Caprio together don't look like a likable pair.
Agreed. The dynamic is interesting. Do you typically watch movies set in specific time periods?
It depends. If a movie looks good or it's by a director I like I will. But I'm not necessarily a fan of period pieces. They often feel stuffy to me.
I agree with that. It's not exactly my thing either.
For this I feel that Luhrman was really attracted to the star potential and the lavish sets he could use in the movie, and not so much in the story.
Yea, he seems to like the extravagence more than anything else.

I don't think he ever made a movie that was not over the to
p in terms of splashiness.
haha right!? Stick to what you know i guess
If you ever do watch the movie, the scene from the plaze through the end of the movie is the climax of it all.
Yeah... I think with him it's more like he can't help himself - he has to spread it thick.
Is it worth watching the movie though?
I like intense movies as much as anyone else and sometimes a few good scenes will make it worthwhile for me.

Personally, I would say no. One of the critics said it best, it's a just 
spectacle.
I know. If the guy was a fashion designer, everything he'd do would be covered in sequins and glitter.
So there is no touching moment in the movie?

Thats the thing though, the scenes that are supposed to be super intense and make the movie/book, are rushed through and not given enough time.They spend more time focusing on Gatsby's parties, not on the real plot.
Ha! Not a big surprise though.
Well, gotta go, it was fun chatting with you.

uid2response.feedback: I have done this HIT before and truly enjoy it. It is fun. This user seemed more interested in my opinions than on the document though.
